      heading: '',
      content: '<p><strong>The Standard of Evidence</strong></p>' +
        '<p>The historical chapters that follow draw on primary sources wherever possible \u2014 the actual texts, inscriptions, legal codes, philosophical treatises, and literary works that constitute the primary record of each civilization\u2019s moral life. They also draw on the best available secondary scholarship in history, philosophy, anthropology, and moral psychology. The citation apparatus at the back of this volume provides the scholarly grounding for the narrative\u2019s claims.</p>' +
        '<p>But the standard of evidence this book applies is not purely textual. It is also consequentialist in the historical sense: the test of whether a civilization\u2019s moral framework was genuinely aligned with the settled truths is not only what the civilization said about virtue but what its actual practice produced. A civilization that proclaimed justice while practicing systematic exploitation fails the test of alignment regardless of the sophistication of its philosophical literature. A civilization whose moral framework was less elaborately theorized but more consistently practiced passes the test more convincingly. Words are evidence. Consequences are evidence too\u2014and in many cases, the more reliable of the two.</p>' +
        '<p>This is the standard that history itself applies, without sentiment and without appeal. Civilizations that aligned their drivers with the settled truths have produced coherence, trust, and the conditions for sustained flourishing. Civilizations that allowed their drivers to scale beyond the ordering capacity of those truths have produced fractures in their persons, their institutions, and ultimately in the civilizations themselves. The historical record is the laboratory in which moral gravity has been tested across five thousand years of human experiment. The chapters that follow are the results.</p>'
